1. Secure php.ini Settings
When a PHP application encounters an error, its default behavior can leak highly sensitive information 
(paths, database queries, stack traces) to attackers.

The Vulnerability (Insecure php.ini)
Ini, TOML
; INSECURE PRODUCTION SETTINGS
display_errors = On
display_startup_errors = On
expose_php = On
disable_functions = ""
If an attacker triggers a database error on a page, they might see something like this rendered directly in their browser:

Fatal error: Uncaught PDOException: SQLSTATE[HY000] [2002] Connection refused in /var/www/html/includes/db.php:14...

The Fix (Secure php.ini)
Ini, TOML
; SECURE PRODUCTION SETTINGS
display_errors = Off
display_startup_errors = Off
log_errors = On
error_log = /var/log/php/errors.log
expose_php = Off
disable_functions = exec,passthru,shell_exec,system,proc_open,popen
2. Minimizing Attack Surface (Removing Modules)
Every active PHP module introduces potential zero-day vulnerabilities. If your application doesn't use a module, disable it.

Step 1: Check active modules

Bash
php -m
Step 2: Disable unused modules (e.g., if you don't use SQLite, FTP, or SNMP)
On Ubuntu/Debian systems running PHP 8.x:

Bash
sudo phpdismod sqlite3 ftp snmp
sudo systemctl restart php8.x-fpm
3. Tracking and Applying PHP/Dependency Updates
Outdated third-party packages are an easy entry point for supply-chain attacks.

Automate Vulnerability Scanning: Use Composer's native auditing tool within your deployment pipeline to check for known vulnerabilities in your dependencies.


command: composer audit
Updating Dependencies Safely:

# Update minor/patch versions within your composer.json constraints
composer update --no-dev --optimize-autoloader


4. Secure File Permissions and Directory Structures
A common flaw is placing core application logic, configuration files, and vendor libraries inside the public web root. If the PHP engine fails or is misconfigured, your source code could be downloaded as plain text.

Secure Directory Layout

/var/www/my-secure-app/
├── config/             <-- OUTSIDE web root (Contains database credentials)
├── src/                <-- OUTSIDE web root (Core application code)
├── vendor/             <-- OUTSIDE web root (Composer packages)
└── public/             <-- PUBLIC WEB ROOT (Only folder exposed to the web)
    ├── index.php       <-- Front Controller
    └── assets/         <-- CSS, JS, Images

Lock Down Permissions (Linux CLI)
The web server (e.g., www-data) should be able to read files, but it should never have write permissions to your PHP source code files unless explicitly required (like a dedicated uploads/ directory).


# Change ownership to root, set group to web server
sudo chown -R root:www-data /var/www/my-secure-app

# Directory permissions: Directories 755 (rwxr-xr-x), Files 644 (rw-r--r--)
find /var/www/my-secure-app -type d -exec chmod 755 {} \;
find /var/www/my-secure-app -type f -exec chmod 644 {} \;

# Make the uploads folder writeable by the web server, but block execution (via .htaccess/Nginx)
sudo chmod -R 775 /var/www/my-secure-app/public/uploads
